		<Placemark id="0A981C3A6A3F2D3C6D14">
			<name>Kirkuk–Ceyhan Oil Pipeline</name>
			<description>Status: Turkish export section operational; original Kirkuk–Baiji–Fish Khabur section under rehabilitation.

The Iraq–Turkey Pipeline, commonly known as the Kirkuk–Ceyhan Pipeline, is a cross-border crude oil export system linking northern Iraq to the Mediterranean oil terminal of Ceyhan in Türkiye. The system includes Iraqi and Turkish pipeline sections and has historically transported crude from the Kirkuk area. The Turkish section is also used to carry crude arriving from the Kurdistan Export Pipeline at Fish Khabur.

Operational status: Partially operational / operational export corridor.

As of July 2026, crude exports through the Iraq–Turkey corridor to Ceyhan are operating again after flows resumed in late 2025. Iraq and Türkiye were also preparing a one-year extension of the bilateral pipeline agreement. However, the original federal Iraqi section running directly from Kirkuk through Baiji to Fish Khabur had remained damaged or inactive for many years and was still being repaired or redeveloped.</description>
